<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Hurricane Experts</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 10, 2004</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004112dbb4b0febbb69c3500721e"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Several University of Central Florida professors are available to talk with news reporters about topics related to hurricanes. They are experts in areas such as the statistical probabilities of storms hitting Florida, the effects of hurricanes on storm-water and the stress that hurricanes can impose on families.</p><p>Contact information for each professor is listed below. If you have trouble reaching any of the professors directly, feel free to call Chad Binette, university writer, at 407-823-6312 (office), 407-247-8777 (cell) or <a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">cbinette@mail.ucf.edu</a>, or Tom Evelyn, assistant director of News and Information,Â at 407-823-5988 (office), 407-928-0524 (cell) or <a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Statistical aspects of hurricane modeling and forecasting</strong>. Mark Johnson, a statistics professor, can discuss aspects such as the probability of Hurricane Ivan hitting Florida or Central Florida. He also can talk about the probability of three hurricanes hitting Florida in one year. Johnson was a visiting scientist at the National Hurricane Center in 1996. Contact: 407-823-2695, <a href="mailto:mejohnso@mail.ucf.edu">mejohnso@mail.ucf.edu</a>. For more information on hurricane forecasts and projected damage estimates based on weather data, go to <a href="http://hurricane.methaz.org/">http://hurricane.methaz.org</a>, a Web site that Johnson and a colleague maintain.</p><p>-- <strong>Impact on storm-water systems</strong>. Martin Wanielista, director of the Stormwater Management Academy and professor of engineering; contact: 407-823-4144, <a href="mailto:wanielis@mail.ucf.edu">wanielis@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Impact on the tourism industry</strong>. Abraham Pizam, dean of the Rosen College of Hospitality Management; contact: 407-903-8010, <a href="mailto:apizam@mail.ucf.edu">apizam@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Impact on families and children</strong>. Ana Leon, associate professor of social work, can also discuss the ways that parents can help children cope with the damage and stress associated with storms. Contact: 407-823-6195, <a href="mailto:leon@mail.ucf.edu">leon@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Impact on the presidential campaigns and other elections</strong>. Roger Handberg, chairman of the Political Science Department; contact: 407-823-2608, <a href="mailto:handberg@mail.ucf.edu">handberg@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Economic impact</strong>. Mark Soskin, associate professor of economics; contact: 386-506-4015, <a href="mailto:soskin@mail.ucf.edu">soskin@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Nurse staffing issues during natural disasters</strong>. School of Nursing professors Jacqueline Byers, 407-823-6311, <a href="mailto:jbyers@mail.ucf.edu">jbyers@mail.ucf.edu</a>; Mary Lou Sole, 407-823-5133, <a href="mailto:msole@mail.ucf.edu">msole@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p><p>-- <strong>Impact on homeowners' insurance policies</strong>. Stanley Smith, SunTrust Chair of Banking and professor of finance; contact: 407-823-6453, <a href="mailto:stan.smith@bus.ucf.edu">stan.smith@bus.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
